  "extension_b_memory_system_effect": {
    "description": "Effect of memory-system retrieval on refusal-pattern response scores. Tests whether reciting retrieved facts in an otherwise abstaining response inflates the 5-judge primary score relative to pure C5 refusals (no retrieval) or C4 factdump refusals (facts in context, no retrieval).",
    "methodology": {
      "refusal_detection": "Same 27-marker abstention regex used in Extension A and the base agent.",
      "recitation_detection": "Heuristic: each retrieved fact is split into 4-word grams (≥15 char), lowercased, substring-matched against the response text. A response \"recites\" if at least one such gram appears verbatim. Zep-graph noise tokens (e.g. \"('communities', None)\") are filtered out before n-gram extraction.",
      "limitation": "The recitation detector has false positives (common phrases like \"the autobiography describes\" can match) and false negatives (paraphrased facts will not match). Letta fullpipeline retrievals are sometimes raw passages of the held-out text, which makes recitation detection trivially positive in those cells. Treat as a first-pass signal."
    },
